  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The first open home sets the tone for your entire campaign. Buyers form impressions within the first sixty seconds of walking through the door, and those impressions are hard to shift regardless of what they see next. The practical preparation that goes into each open home is not glamorous work, but it has a measurable effect on how buyers perceive the property and, ultimately, on the offers you receive. Most of it comes down to consistency and attention to detail rather than major outlay.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The week before your first open home</h2>
      <p>If the property is professionally styled, the stylist will handle the furniture and decorative layer. What remains is your responsibility. Work through each room systematically and remove anything that makes the space feel cluttered or personal. Family photos, children's artwork on the fridge, excess furniture that makes rooms feel smaller, and personal items in bathrooms should all be packed away or removed from the property entirely. Buyers need to see the space as a potential home for themselves, not a snapshot of your life in it.</p>

      <p>Address visible maintenance items before the first open. A dripping tap, a stiff door hinge, a cracked tile in the bathroom, or peeling paint on the front fence are small things individually. Together they create an impression that the property has not been looked after, and buyers use those observations to justify lower offers or to negotiate harder on price. Your agent should walk through with you before you list and give you a clear list of what is worth fixing and what to leave.</p>

      <p>The garden and exterior should be at their best before the first inspection. In Brisbane, first impressions start from the street. Mow the lawn, edge the garden beds, remove any dead plants, clean the driveway, and clear the front path of leaves or debris. If the front fence or gate needs a coat of paint, do it. Buyers arriving to an open home decide whether they are interested before they reach the front door.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The morning of an open home</h2>
      <p>Give yourself at least two hours of preparation time on the morning of each inspection. The goal is to present the property in the same condition as the marketing photography, or as close to it as possible. Buyers have seen those photos online and arrive with a specific expectation. When the property matches or exceeds what they saw in the photographs, it reinforces their interest. When it falls short, it creates doubt.</p>

      <p>Clean every surface that buyers will touch or look at closely. Kitchen benches, stovetop, bathroom vanities, toilet, shower screen, and mirrors. Run a vacuum through the main living areas and bedrooms. If there are pets, remove them from the property and their bedding or feeding bowls as well. Pet odours are consistently cited by buyers as one of the strongest deterrents, particularly in the indoor living areas. A professionally cleaned property is worth considering for the first inspection if deep cleaning is not part of your regular routine.</p>

      <p>Temperature matters more than most sellers realise. In Brisbane, an open home on a warm day with all the windows closed and no air conditioning running tells buyers something unflattering about how the property manages heat. On warm days, get the air conditioning running for at least 30 minutes before the open home begins so the property is at a comfortable temperature when buyers arrive. In winter, the same principle applies in reverse. A warm, inviting interior on a cool Brisbane morning creates a strong positive impression.</p>

      <p>Open all curtains and blinds in every room before buyers arrive. Natural light is one of the most universally valued qualities in a home, and a bright, open interior reads as larger and more appealing than a dim one. Turn on all interior lights as well, including under-cabinet kitchen lighting and lamps in living areas. The additional warm light makes the property feel considered and lived in, even when you have already moved out.</p>

      <p>Leave the property before the open home starts and do not return until after it has finished. Your presence as the owner changes the dynamic for buyers. They feel watched and uncomfortable asking their agent questions or spending time in rooms they are interested in. Buyers who are genuinely interested need the freedom to move through the property at their own pace, and they are far more likely to do that when the owner is not present.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After the inspection</h2>
      <p>The period immediately following each open home is when your agent should be most active. Within 24 hours, every attendee who expressed interest should receive a follow-up call or message. This is not just courtesy. It is the process through which serious buyers are identified, questions are answered, and the conditions for an offer are established. An agent who does not systematically follow up after open homes is leaving money on the table regardless of how well the inspection went.</p>

      <p>Ask your agent for a debrief after every open home. You want to know how many groups attended, what feedback buyers gave on price and presentation, and whether any parties have requested a contract or indicated they want a private inspection. Tracking this information across multiple open homes gives you a clear picture of where buyer interest is concentrated and whether your price expectations are aligned with the market's response.</p>

      <p>If attendance is lower than expected or price feedback is consistently below your expectations, this is useful information, not a crisis. It tells you something about pricing or presentation that is worth addressing rather than ignoring. The worst outcome in a sale campaign is spending four weeks at the wrong price with insufficient feedback to recognise it. Active vendor reporting after each open home prevents that from happening.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Consistency across the campaign</h2>
      <p>First open homes typically attract the highest attendance, because buyers who have been watching the market respond quickly to new listings. By the second and third open homes, attendance may be lower but buyer quality is often higher. The buyers who return for a second visit or request private inspections after the first open home are the most serious ones. Maintain the same level of preparation for every inspection regardless of whether you expect 30 groups or five.</p>

      <p>A property that presents consistently well across every open home sends a message to buyers about how it has been maintained. Buyers notice when a property looks slightly less cared for at the second inspection. That observation feeds into their negotiating position. Keeping the standard high throughout the campaign protects you from unnecessary discounting in the final stages.</p>

